        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Two audiences, one interface</h2>
            <p>The interface has to teach two learning paths at once.</p>
            <div class="learnability-goal">
                <h3>Designing for learnability</h3>
                <div class="user-types">
                    <div class="user-type">
                        <strong>New to SysML</strong>
                        <p>Engineers who need MBSE but have not used SysML. The tool teaches them through use, with progressive disclosure, clear feedback, and room to explore safely.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="user-type">
                        <strong>v1 to v2 transition</strong>
                        <p>Experienced users adjusting to v2 terminology. Show the familiar names next to their v2 equivalents.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Process</h2>
            <div class="process-steps">
                <div class="process-step complete">
                    <span class="num">01</span><strong>Principles</strong>
                    <p>Values &amp; decision criteria</p>
                </div>
                <div class="process-step complete">
                    <span class="num">02</span><strong>Interface analysis</strong>
                    <p>Current state audit</p>
                </div>
                <div class="process-step">
                    <span class="num">03</span><strong>IA</strong>
                    <p>Content hierarchy</p>
                </div>
                <div class="process-step">
                    <span class="num">04</span><strong>Onboarding</strong>
                    <p>First-run experience</p>
                </div>
                <div class="process-step">
                    <span class="num">05</span><strong>Design foundations</strong>
                    <p>Tokens &amp; patterns</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>The order matters. Principles make the decisions defensible. The analysis shows where they hold and where the gaps are. IA settles where things live. The design system comes last, because tokens are expensive to change once they are in production.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Design principles</h2>
            <p>Ten principles drawn from UX and information design, then checked with Cauê against how systems engineers actually work. Green marks the ones that directly support learnability.</p>
            <div class="sources-strip">
                <div class="sources-strip-label">Synthesized from</div>
                <div class="sources-strip-content">
                    <strong>Tufte</strong> (data-ink, layering, small multiples) · <strong>Bertin</strong> (visual variables) · <strong>Nielsen</strong> (heuristics) · <strong>Shneiderman</strong> (overview and detail, linked views) · <strong>Norman</strong> (affordances, safe exploration) · <strong>Cognitive load</strong> (Sweller, Miller) · <strong>SysML v2 specification</strong> · domain review with a practicing systems engineer.
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="principles-grid">
                <div class="principle-card">
                    <div class="principle-num">01</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>One model, many views</strong>
                        <p>One source of truth. Diagram, tree, table, and text stay in sync. <span class="principle-source">Shneiderman; linked views</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card learnability">
                    <div class="principle-num">02</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Consistent visual grammar</strong>
                        <p>The same meaning gets the same appearance, so patterns become easy to spot. <span class="principle-source">Bertin; Tufte</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card learnability">
                    <div class="principle-num">03</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Progressive disclosure</strong>
                        <p>Show what the task needs and keep the rest out of the way. <span class="principle-source">Miller's Law; NNGroup</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card">
                    <div class="principle-num">04</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Click anywhere, land everywhere</strong>
                        <p>A selection syncs across every view at once. <span class="principle-source">Linked views</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card learnability">
                    <div class="principle-num">05</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Context preservation</strong>
                        <p>Zoom in without losing your place. Orientation supports learning. <span class="principle-source">Shneiderman's mantra</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card">
                    <div class="principle-num">06</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Type-first organization</strong>
                        <p>Group by element type rather than by creation order. <span class="principle-source">IA</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card">
                    <div class="principle-num">07</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Edge density management</strong>
                        <p>Filter or limit edges so the diagram stays readable. <span class="principle-source">Tufte: layering and separation</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card">
                    <div class="principle-num">08</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Validation timing</strong>
                        <p>Let the user choose real-time or on-demand checks. <span class="principle-source">B2B expert workflows</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card learnability">
                    <div class="principle-num">09</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Safe exploration</strong>
                        <p>Generous undo and non-destructive defaults, so mistakes stay cheap. <span class="principle-source">Norman</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="principle-card learnability">
                    <div class="principle-num">10</div>
                    <div class="principle-content">
                        <strong>Leverage familiar patterns</strong>
                        <p>Build on IDE and CAD conventions people already know. <span class="principle-source">Jakob's Law</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">SysML v2 constraint map</h2>
            <p>Where the spec constrains design, and where it does not. Shape and semantics are fixed. Presentation is where learnability happens.</p>
            <div class="constraint-detail">
                <div class="constraint-detail-header">
                    <span class="label fixed">Fixed</span>
                    <h4>Set by the SysML v2 specification</h4>
                </div>
                <table class="constraint-table fixed">
                    <thead>
                        <tr><th>Element</th><th>Standard representation</th></tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Part def / Part usage</td><td>Rectangle with «part def» / «part» keyword</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Composition</td><td>Filled diamond on the parent end</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Port / Connector</td><td>Small square on the block edge, line between ports</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Requirement</td><td>Rectangle with «requirement» and an id field</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>State / Transition</td><td>Rounded rectangle, arrow with a trigger label</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <div class="constraint-detail">
                <div class="constraint-detail-header">
                    <span class="label flexible">Flexible</span>
                    <h4>Open to design</h4>
                </div>
                <table class="constraint-table flexible">
                    <thead>
                        <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Design freedom</th></tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Color</td><td>Unspecified. Can encode type, subsystem, status, or health.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Size</td><td>Can encode information, such as child count or criticality.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Layout and edge routing</td><td>Auto-layout, spacing, alignment, orthogonal or curved, bundling.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Hierarchy display</td><td>Containment or separate diagrams.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Labels, filtering, animation</td><td>Defaults, truncation, hover expansion, visibility, zoom transitions.</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <div class="constraint-boundary-note">
                <strong>Why the boundary matters:</strong> shape is fixed, while color, size, and layout are presentation. If you keep the layers separate, so that shape means type, color means status, and size means magnitude, each one stays readable on its own.
            </div>
        </section>

