        <section>
            <div class="recommendations-box">
                <h3>Concrete recommendations</h3>
                <p class="recommendations-intro">Near-term moves, ordered by how much downstream work each one unblocks.</p>
                <ol class="recommendations-list">
                    <li><strong>Resolve Model Explorer versus File Explorer.</strong> This is the biggest IA decision. It gates the sidebar hierarchy, the icon weight, and the default view.</li>
                    <li><strong>Bridge v1 and v2 in search.</strong> Typing "Block" should surface "Part" with the v1 label still visible. Small to build, high in value.</li>
                    <li><strong>Standardize icon style and hover behavior.</strong> Mixed flat and filled icons weaken the visual grammar. Clean this up in one pass before the IA hardens.</li>
                    <li><strong>Map the core workflows end to end.</strong> Create, add parts, connect, then review and validate. This surfaces gaps that a static audit misses.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extend the teaching tooltips.</strong> Grow the Part tooltip pattern across the palette. This is the strongest lever for learning through use.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Working with AI</h2>
            <p>A few things I learned about using AI on this project.</p>
            <div class="ai-notes">
                <div class="ai-note">
                    <p><strong>AI is good at synthesizing frameworks, but the knowledge does not come from AI.</strong> It pulled the ten principles together quickly. The frameworks themselves come from people like Tufte, Bertin, and Norman. To know that Miller's Law is the reason for progressive disclosure, I had to read the source, not the summary.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="ai-note">
                    <p><strong>AI gets you basic knowledge faster, but experts and real users hold the real-world detail.</strong> It brought me up to speed on SysML v2. How a systems engineer actually works, and where they stall, came from Cauê, not from a model.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="ai-note">
                    <p><strong>AI expands scope quickly, and it does so differently for different people.</strong> It does not weigh the consequences for a team unless you ask it to. Different roles and experts set boundaries in different ways. So the problem, the role, and the scope have to be defined clearly. Those definitions are what keep the output inside what the work actually needs.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Reflection</h2>
            <div class="reflection">
                <p><strong>A limit I could not resolve:</strong> learnability can only be tested with real users in the middle of a task. Until that happens, every principle here is a hypothesis. The recommendations are ranked by leverage, not by evidence.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="reflection">
                <p>Most MBSE tools assume training. System Forge asks what happens if the interface teaches instead. Every tooltip, cue, and error message becomes a chance to help someone learn the language while they use it.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

